# 🔹 Why Do We Need ConfigMap & Secrets?

In real-world applications, we deploy the same app across multiple environments:

* DEV (Development)
* SIT (Testing)
* UAT (Client Testing)
* PILOT (Pre-Production)
* PRODUCTION (Live)

👉 Each environment has **different configurations** like:

* Database URL
* Username / Password
* Kafka / Redis configs
* SMTP settings

❌ Hardcoding these values in code makes your app:

* Rigid
* Hard to maintain
* Not portable

✅ Solution:

Use **ConfigMap & Secrets** to make your app **flexible and environment-independent**

---

# 🔹 ConfigMap (Non-Sensitive Data)

ConfigMap stores **plain configuration values** in key-value format.

👉 Example: DB URL, Driver, Username

---

## 🔸 ConfigMap Manifest

```yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: ashokit-config-map
  labels:
    storage: ashokit-db-config-map
data:
  DB_DRIVER: com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver
  DB_URL: jdbc:mysql://mysqldb:3306/sbms
  DB_USERNAME: root
```

---

## 🔸 Apply ConfigMap

```bash
kubectl apply -f configmap.yml
```

---

## 🔸 Use ConfigMap in Pod

```yaml
- name: DB_DRIVER
  valueFrom:
    configMapKeyRef:
      name: ashokit-config-map
      key: DB_DRIVER
```

---

# 🔹 Secrets (Sensitive Data 🔐)

Secrets store **confidential data** such as:

* Passwords
* Tokens
* API keys

👉 Data must be **Base64 encoded**

---

## 🔸 Secret Manifest

```yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata:
  name: ashokit-secret
  labels:
    storage: ashokit-db-secret
type: Opaque
data:
  DB_PASSWORD: cm9vdA==
```

---

## 🔸 Apply Secret

```bash
kubectl apply -f secret.yml
```

---

## 🔸 Use Secret in Pod

```yaml
- name: DB_PASSWORD
  valueFrom:
    secretKeyRef:
      name: ashokit-secret
      key: DB_PASSWORD
```

---

# 🔹 Real Example (Combined Usage)

👉 Instead of hardcoding:

```yaml
spring:
  datasource:
    driver-class-name: com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver
    url: jdbc:mysql://mysqldb:3306/sbms
    username: root
    password: root
```

👉 Use environment variables:

```yaml
spring:
  datasource:
    driver-class-name: ${DB_DRIVER}
    url: ${DB_URL}
    username: ${DB_USERNAME}
    password: ${DB_PASSWORD}
```

---

# 🔹 How Everything Connects

```text
ConfigMap → Stores normal config
Secret → Stores sensitive data
        ↓
Pod reads both using valueFrom
        ↓
App uses env variables
        ↓
Same Docker image works in all environments 🚀
```

---

# 🔹 Key Differences

| Feature   | ConfigMap     | Secret                                |
| --------- | ------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Data Type | Non-sensitive | Sensitive                             |
| Encoding  | Plain text    | Base64 encoded                        |
| Use Case  | Config values | Passwords / tokens                    |
| Security  | Low           | Higher (but not encrypted by default) |

---

# 🔹 Important Notes

* ConfigMap & Secrets **decouple config from code**
* No need to rebuild Docker image for environment changes
* Makes your app **portable & scalable**
* Used heavily in **production-grade systems**

---

# 🚀 Final Takeaway

* Use **ConfigMap** for normal configuration
* Use **Secrets** for confidential data
* Never hardcode values inside your application
* This is a **must-know concept for DevOps & Kubernetes interviews**

